      "prompt": "Proof: from a square and an equilateral triangle",
      "diagram": {
        "mode": "static",
        "variant": "special-triangles"
      },
      "blanks": [
        {
          "stage": 1,
          "prompt": "Cut a unit square along its diagonal d. By the Pythagorean theorem d² = 1² + 1² = ?",
          "answer": 2,
          "hint": "1 + 1 = 2, so the diagonal is √2."
        },
        {
          "stage": 2,
          "prompt": "An equilateral triangle has three equal angles that add to 180°. Each one is 180 ÷ 3 = ?",
          "answer": 60,
          "unit": "°",
          "hint": "180 ÷ 3."
        },
        {
          "stage": 3,
          "prompt": "Drop the height h of that side-2 triangle. By the Pythagorean theorem h² = 2² − 1² = ?",
          "answer": 3,
          "hint": "4 − 1 = 3, so the long leg is √3."
        }
      ],
      "stages": [
        "Start with a square of side 1 and draw a diagonal. It splits the square into two identical right triangles, each with two 45° angles.",
        "By the Pythagorean theorem the diagonal is √(1² + 1²) = √2. So a 45-45-90 triangle has sides 1 : 1 : √2.",
        "Now take an equilateral triangle of side 2 — every angle 60° — and drop a height from the top. It cuts the base into two 1's and splits the top angle into two 30°s.",
        "By the Pythagorean theorem that height is √(2² − 1²) = √3. So a 30-60-90 triangle has sides 1 : √3 : 2."
      ]
    },
